<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1934-08-03T19:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1934-08-03T19:00:00-05:00" n="290" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d290">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">611.1431/57: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Minister in Guatemala</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Hanna</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                                State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Guatemala</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1934-08-03T18:00:00-06:00">August 3, 1934—6
                                p.m.</date><lb/>[Received 10:05 p.m.]</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>51. My despatch No. 258, July 24. Minister for Foreign Affairs told me
                            this morning that under existing circumstances he could hardly expect in
                            near future a definition of Germany’s attitude on trade matters with
                            Guatemala but that regardless of Germany’s attitude his Government
                            expects to give consideration to any proposals the Government of the
                            United States might care to make when the prospective conversations are
                            opened about September 1st.</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Hanna</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
